{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a6c75764-0faf-4372-a72f-aefc57e9d56a","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your process and collect:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps                          # get the PID\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**3. Copy the trace out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**4. Analyze** by opening `trace.nettrace` in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert to Speedscope:\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format speedscope\n```\nThen open at [speedscope.app](https://www.speedscope.app).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools (read-only filesystem), use a **sidecar** or **ephemeral debug container** (`kubectl debug`).\n- For production, consider `--buffersize 512` if you're dropping events.\n- `dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>` is a good quick first look before tracing.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f554939c-e6e8-41e7-a609-eecbeac20869","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge question, not a code task, so I'll answer directly.","outputTokens":388},"id":"d70b2f04-098b-46a9-8e87-dbfcc9891c91","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:53:27.951Z","parentId":"61488cfb-3c40-4505-90d1-32707d296fbc"}
